:"omkring 1200–Afdød","1200–Male":"1200–Afdød","1205–Female":"1205–Afdød","1225–1264":"1225–1264","1175–1264":"1175–1264","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1264":"1264","1175":"1175","about 1200":"omkring 1200","Letheringham, Suffolk, England":"Letheringham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"about 1200–":"circa 1200–Overleden","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1205–Female":"1205–Overleden","1225–1264":"1225–1264","1175–1264":"1175–1264","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1264":"1264","1175":"1175","about 1200":"circa 1200","Letheringham, Suffolk, England":"Letheringham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"about 1200–":"about 1200–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1205–Female":"1205–Deceased","1225–1264":"1225–1264","1175–1264":"1175–1264","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1264":"1264","1175":"1175","about 1200":"about 1200","Letheringham, Suffolk, England":"Letheringham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bovile","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy whose medieval forms share a similar range of variants, such as Bouville (Seine-Maritime), any of several places called Biéville (Calvados, Manche) or Biville (Manche, Seine-Maritime), Beuzeville-la-Giffard (Seine-Maritime), Boiville (Orne), and perhaps Boudeville (Seine-Maritime). See also   Boswell   and   Beville  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Boswell","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Beuzeville-la-Giffard in Seine-Maritime, France, named with the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Boso</i> + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. The final element has been altered as a result of association with the common placename ending <i>-well</i> ‘spring, stream’. Some instances of   Bovill   may have the same origin."]},{"name":"Beville","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Surrey; of Norman origin): variant of   Bovill  . Derivation from Beuville (Calvados) is also possible, though unproven.","French (also <b>Béville</b>): habitational name from Béville (Moselle) or Béville-le-Comte (Eure-et-Loir), or a variant of <b>Beuville</b>, a habitational name from Beuville (Calvados). The surname <i>Béville</i> is rare in France."]},{"name":"Buffalo","meanings":["English: apparently an American English nickname from <i>buffalo</i>, perhaps denoting a large, powerfully built man. Alternatively, perhaps an altered form of an unidentified surname, possibly English   Bovill  . Compare   Buffaloe   and   Buffalow  .","Native American: translation into English (and shortening) of a personal name based on a word, such as Lakota and Dakota Sioux <i>tataŋka</i> and Cheyenne <i>hotoa'e</i>, meaning ‘buffalo’ or ‘bull’. See also   Bull   5.","History: Majority of the Buffalos trace their origin to the brothers Arthur and William Buffelow, who were recorded in NC in 1750s. Their surname was (later) also spelled <i>Buffalow</i>, <i>Buffaloe</i>, and <i>Buffalo</i>. The word <i>buffalo</i> is even nowadays often misspelled <i>buffelow</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":59,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdic